audit_report:
1. YES
2. - Missing access control / Unrestricted delegatecall (lines 7–8): forward is public and allows any caller to delegatecall an arbitrary callee with arbitrary data, executing in the Proxy’s context; an attacker can modify storage (e.g., overwrite owner), drain funds, or take arbitrary actions.
   - Destructibility via delegatecall (lines 7–8): the callee’s code can execute selfdestruct via delegatecall, destroying the Proxy and sending its balance to an attacker-controlled address.
   - Owner unused (lines 3–7): owner is set (line 5) but never enforced on forward, creating an authorization bypass where intended ownership provides no protection.

1. YES
2. - Missing access control (lines 3-6,10): Anyone can trigger transferFrom() to move tokens from any from with allowance; no msg.sender == from or auth check.
   - Unchecked low-level call (line 10): caddress.call(...) forwards all gas, may hit fallback if selector absent, ignores success flag; failures are silent and function still returns true.
   - Reentrancy risk (line 10): External call without guard or CEI pattern enables malicious token/fallback to reenter.
   - Gas/DoS via unbounded recursion (lines 8-12): Recursive loop over user-controlled _tos can exhaust gas/stack; no short-circuit on failures.
3. N/A
4. N/A

1. YES
2. - Reentrancy + unchecked ether send (lines 86-89, esp. 87): uses _addr.call.value(_wei) before updating state and without checking the return value, enabling reentrancy and/or silent fund loss/inconsistency. 
   - Unchecked low-level external call (line 34): token.call(...) ignores return value, allowing silent failure and state desync. 
   - Owner variable shadowing/access control confusion (lines 4, 28, 45): Token redeclares owner, so onlyOwner checks Ownable.owner while initTokenBank sets Token.owner, leading to mistaken privilege assumptions. 
   - Public initializer (lines 42-47): initTokenBank is public and not a constructor; anyone can call it to set Token.owner and MinDeposit, increasing misconfiguration risk. 
   - Arithmetic overflow risk (lines 59, 88): no SafeMath; Holders[msg.sender] += msg.value can overflow; subtraction relies on a prior check but still uses unchecked arithmetic. 
   - Logic flaw mixing token/ETH balances (lines 67-70): WitdrawTokenToHolder zeroes Holders[_to] (ETH balance) when transferring tokens, letting owner wipe ETH balances unrelated to token transfer. 
   - Silent auth failure (lines 22-24): onlyOwner doesn’t revert on failure, causing no-op instead of fail-fast, which can mask misuse.
3. N/A
4. N/A

1) YES. 
2) Vulnerabilities: Unchecked low-level call with ignored return and all-gas forward to arbitrary target (line: caddress.call(id, from, _tos[i], v[i])) enables silent failure and reentrancy/DoS; Missing array-length check (transfer lacks require(_tos.length == v.length)) while indexing v[i] can revert/DoS (lines: function transfer(...), v[i]); Unbounded recursion over user input can exhaust gas (line: return transferRecursive(...)); Missing authorization allows anyone to initiate allowance-based transfers from arbitrary from to arbitrary _tos via any caddress (line: function transfer(...)).

1. YES
2. Vulnerabilities:
   - Timestamp dependence (block timestamp manipulation) — line 4: using block.timestamp to gate critical logic lets miners skew the result near the cutoff, potentially ending/continuing the sale slightly earlier/later.
   - Outdated/floating compiler pragma — line 1: ^0.4.25 allows varying 0.4.x compilers (some with known bugs) and lacks modern safety checks; pin exact version and upgrade to >=0.8.x.
   - Hardcoded past cutoff — lines 7–12: 1546300800 (2019-01-01) makes the check always true in 2025, causing isSaleFinished to always return true, which can be a business-logic DoS (sale permanently finished).
